oncept of mode as applied to pitch relationships generally,\nHarold S. Powers describes a continuum between abstract scale and specific\ntune, with \"most of the area between ... being in the domain of mode\" (Powers\n2001, Â§I,3).\n","linknr":640,"url":"Mode_(music)","recorded":1362552217,"links":112,"instances":["music","music","music","music","professor_of_music","music","music","music","music","music","composer","music","music","music"],"pdf":["http://www.bpmonline.org.uk/bpm11/ordoulidis_the_greek_popular_modes.pdf"],"categories":["Modes|","Melody types","Ancient Greek music","Catholic music"],"headings":["Modes and scales","Greek","Western Church","Modern","Other types","Analogues in different musical traditions","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Dorian_mode_C.png/300px-Dorian_mode_C.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Greek_Dorian_enharmonic_genus.png/300px-Greek_Dorian_enharmonic_genus.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Greek_Dorian_chromatic_genus.png/300px-Greek_Dorian_chromatic_genus.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Dorian_diatonic.png/300px-Dorian_diatonic.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/JubilateDeoIntr